Commentaries on the Arz'tlmzetica began to appear very early. Probably the most interesting commentary from the modern point of view was the one written in the late fourth or early fifth cen— tury by Hypatia, the daughter of Theon of Alexandria. Unfortu- nately her writings are all lost, although there is ground for the beliefl that some remarks made by Michael Psellus (eleventh century) concerning Egyptian arithmetic ancl algebra were based on her commentary. She came naturally by her mathematical ability; her father Theon wrote a commentary on Ptolemy's Almagest and makes in this the earliest known reference to Diophantus.
